Installing Operators Using the Web Console (OpenShift)
1️⃣ What is an Operator?
An Operator in Red Hat OpenShift / Kubernetes is a software extension that automates deployment, configuration, management, and updates of applications.
Think of an operator like an automated administrator for an application.
Example
Instead of manually managing a database:
•	Install DB
•	Configure storage
•	Handle scaling
•	Perform upgrades
The Operator automatically manages all this.
Example Operators:
•	MySQL Operator
•	Prometheus Operator
•	Elasticsearch Operator
________________________________________
2️⃣ Operator Lifecycle Manager (OLM)
The Operator Lifecycle Manager (OLM) manages the complete lifecycle of operators.
Lifecycle includes:
•	Installation
•	Updates
•	Version control
•	Dependencies
•	Removal
OLM automatically manages operators in the cluster.
OLM manages these resources
Resource	Purpose
CSV (ClusterServiceVersion)	Describes a specific operator version
Subscription	Defines how operator updates happen
InstallPlan	Plan used to install/update operator
OperatorGroup	Defines which namespaces operator watches
________________________________________
3️⃣ OperatorHub
OperatorHub is the marketplace for operators.
In OpenShift Web Console:
Operators → OperatorHub
You can:
•	Search operators
•	View operator info
•	Install operators
You can filter operators by:
•	Category
•	Provider
•	Source
•	Subscription required
________________________________________
4️⃣ Steps to Install an Operator (Web Console)
Step 1
Go to
Operators → OperatorHub
Step 2
Select an operator.
Example:
MySQL Operator
Prometheus Operator
Step 3
Click
Install
This opens the Install Operator Wizard.
________________________________________
5️⃣ Important Installation Options
1️⃣ Update Channel
Defines which version stream you receive updates from.
Examples:
Channel	Meaning
stable	Stable production versions
fast	Faster updates but less stable
preview	Experimental versions
Example
channel: stable
Best practice → Use stable
________________________________________
2️⃣ Installation Mode
Determines which namespaces the operator monitors.
Option 1 (Most common)
All namespaces on the cluster
Meaning:
Operator watches all namespaces.
Example:
User creates MySQL custom resource in namespace:
dev-project
Operator automatically deploys MySQL there.
________________________________________
Option 2
A specific namespace
Operator works only in that namespace.
Example
database-operators
________________________________________
3️⃣ Installed Namespace
Defines where the operator itself runs.
Example namespaces:
openshift-operators
operators
custom namespace
Important:
Operator workload runs here, but it may manage apps in other namespaces.
Example
Operator namespace → openshift-operators
Database created → dev-project namespace
________________________________________
4️⃣ Update Approval
Controls operator updates.
Automatic
OLM updates operator automatically.
Automatic
Manual
Admin must approve update.
Manual
Then you approve InstallPlans.
________________________________________
6️⃣ What Happens During Installation
When you click Install, OpenShift creates:
1️⃣ Subscription
Defines update channel and approval.
Example command:
oc get subscription
________________________________________
2️⃣ OperatorGroup
Defines namespaces operator watches.
Command:
oc get operatorgroup
________________________________________
3️⃣ InstallPlan
Installation execution plan.
Command:
oc get installplan
________________________________________
4️⃣ ClusterServiceVersion (CSV)
Represents operator version.
Command:
oc get csv
Example output:
NAME                 DISPLAY                VERSION
mysql-operator.v1    MySQL Operator         1.0
________________________________________
